Describe how you behaved in a stressful situation
- what the situation was
- how you behaved
- how other people might have behaved and explain how you felt about your behaved afterwards

One particularly stressful situation I experienced was during a final exam at university a few years ago. The test covered a large amount of material, and the time was quite limited. To make matters worse, I hadn’t prepared as well as I should have. As soon as the exam started, my heart began to race and my mind went completely blank. However, instead of panicking, I reminded myself that stress is a normal reaction and that I could stay focused. I took a deep breath to calm myself down and regain my concentration.

Throughout the exam, I tried to stay positive and followed a methodical approach. I first skimmed through the questions to get an overview, then focused on answering the ones I felt most confident about. After that, I moved on to the more difficult ones. At one point, I glanced around and noticed that many other students were visibly stressed—some were frantically flipping through their notes, while others seemed completely frozen with anxiety.

Looking back, I felt quite proud of how I managed the situation. Despite the pressure, I was able to stay in control and avoid panicking. I came to realize that maintaining a calm mindset helped me think more clearly and perform more effectively. This experience reinforced the importance of staying composed, not just in exams but in any high-pressure situation I might encounter in the future.
